# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: virtual-geometry-nanite
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] In computer graphics, a **sprite** is a two-dimensional bitmap that is integrated into a larger scene, most often in a 2D video game.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] Originally, the term *sprite* referred to fixed-sized objects composited together, by hardware, with a background.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] Use of the term has since become more general.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] Hardware varies in the number of sprites supported, the size and colors of each sprite, and special effects such as scaling or reporting pixel-precise overlap.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] Hardware composition of sprites occurs as each scan line is prepared for the video output device, such as a cathode-ray tube, without involvement of the main CPU and without the need for a full-screen frame buffer.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] Sprites can be positioned or altered by setting attributes used during the hardware composition process.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] The number of sprites which can be displayed per scan line is often lower than the total number of sprites a system supports.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] For example, the Texas Instruments TMS9918 chip supports 32 sprites, but only four can appear on the same scan line.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] The CPUs in modern computers, video game consoles, and mobile devices are fast enough that bitmaps can be drawn into a frame buffer without special hardware assistance.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] Beyond that, GPUs can render vast numbers of scaled, rotated, anti-aliased, partially translucent, very high resolution images in parallel with the CPU.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] According to Karl Guttag, one of two engineers for the 1979 Texas Instruments TMS9918 video display processor, this use of the word *sprite* came from David Ackley, a manager at TI.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] It was also used by Danny Hillis at Texas Instruments in the late 1970s.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] The term was derived from the fact that sprites "float" on top of the background image without overwriting it, much like a ghost or mythological sprite.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] The use of sprites originated with arcade video games.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] Nolan Bushnell came up with the original concept when he developed the first arcade video game, *Computer Space* (1971).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] Technical limitations made it difficult to adapt the early mainframe game *Spacewar!* (1962), which performed an entire screen refresh for every little movement, so he came up with a solution to the problem: controlling each individual game element with a dedicated transistor.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] The rockets were essentially hardwired bitmaps that moved around the screen independently of the background, an important innovation for producing screen images more efficiently and providing the basis for sprite graphics.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] The earliest video games to represent player characters as human player sprites were arcade sports video games, beginning with Taito's *TV Basketball*, released in April 1974 and licensed to Midway Manufacturing for release in North America.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] Designed by Tomohiro Nishikado, he wanted to move beyond simple *Pong*-style rectangles to character graphics, by rearranging the rectangle shapes into objects that look like basketball players and basketball hoops.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] Ramtek released another sports video game in October 1974, *Baseball*, which similarly displayed human-like characters.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] The Namco Galaxian arcade system board, for the 1979 arcade game *Galaxian*, displays animated, multi-colored sprites over a scrolling background.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] It became the basis for Nintendo's *Radar Scope* and *Donkey Kong* arcade hardware and home consoles such as the Nintendo Entertainment System.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] According to Steve Golson from General Computer Corporation, the term "stamp" was used instead of "sprite" at the time.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] Signetics devised the first chips capable of generating sprite graphics (referred to as *objects* by Signetics) for home systems.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] The Signetics 2636 video processors were first used in the 1978 1292 Advanced Programmable Video System and later in the 1979 Elektor TV Games Computer.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] The Atari VCS, released in 1977, has a hardware sprite implementation where five graphical objects can be moved independently of the game playfield.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] The term *sprite* was not in use at the time.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] The VCS's sprites are called *movable objects* in the programming manual, further identified as two *players*, two *missiles*, and one *ball*.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] These each consist of a single row of pixels that are displayed on a scan line.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] To produce a two-dimensional shape, the sprite's single-row bitmap is altered by software from one scan line to the next.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] The 1979 Atari 400 and 800 home computers have similar, but more elaborate, circuitry capable of moving eight single-color objects per scan line: four 8-bit wide *players* and four 2-bit wide *missiles*.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] Each is the full height of the display—a long, thin strip.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] DMA from a table in memory automatically sets the graphics pattern registers for each scan line.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] Hardware registers control the horizontal position of each player and missile.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] Vertical motion is achieved by moving the bitmap data within a player or missile's strip.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] The feature was called *player/missile graphics* by Atari.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] Texas Instruments developed the TMS9918 chip with sprite support for its 1979 TI-99/4 home computer.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] An updated version is used in the 1981 TI-99/4A.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] Sprites remained popular with the rise of 2.5D games (those which recreate a 3D game space from a 2D map) in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] A technique called billboarding allows 2.5D games to keep onscreen sprites rotated toward the player view at all times.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] Some 2.5D games, such as 1993's *Doom*, allow the same entity to be represented by different sprites depending on its rotation relative to the viewer, furthering the illusion of 3D.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] Fully 3D games usually present world objects as 3D models, but sprites are supported in some 3D game engines, such as GoldSrc and Unreal, and may be billboarded or locked to fixed orientations.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] Sprites remain useful for small details, particle effects, and other applications where the lack of a third dimension is not a major detriment.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/impostor-computer-graphics] These are base hardware specs and do not include additional programming techniques, such as using raster interrupts to repurpose sprites mid-frame.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] In computer graphics, **level of detail** (**LOD**) refers to the complexity of a 3D model representation.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] LOD can be decreased as the model moves away from the viewer or according to other metrics such as object importance, viewpoint-relative speed or position.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] LOD techniques increase the efficiency of rendering by decreasing the workload on graphics pipeline stages, usually vertex transformations.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The reduced visual quality of the model is often unnoticed because of the small effect on object appearance when distant or moving fast.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Although most of the time LOD is applied to geometry detail only, the basic concept can be generalized.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Recently, LOD techniques also included shader management to keep control of pixel complexity.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] A form of level of detail management has been applied to texture maps for years, under the name of mipmapping, also providing higher rendering quality.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] It is commonplace to say that "an object has been *LOD-ed*" when the object is simplified by the underlying *LOD-ing algorithm* as well as a 3D modeler manually creating LOD models.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The origin[1] of all the LOD algorithms for 3D computer graphics can be traced back to an article by James H.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Clark in the October 1976 issue of *Communications of the ACM*.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] At the time, computers were monolithic and rare, and graphics were being driven by researchers.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The hardware itself was completely different, both architecturally and performance-wise.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] As such, many differences could be observed with regard to today's algorithms but also many common points.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The original algorithm presented a much more generic approach to what will be discussed here.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] After introducing some available algorithms for geometry management, it is stated that most fruitful gains came from *"...structuring the environments being rendered"*, allowing to exploit faster transformations and clipping operations.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The proposed algorithm envisions a tree data structure which encodes in its arcs both transformations and transitions to more detailed objects.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] In this way, each node encodes an object and according to a fast heuristic, the tree is descended to the leaves which provide each object with more detail.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] When a leaf is reached, other methods could be used when higher detail is needed, such as Catmull's recursive subdivision[2].
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The paper then introduces clipping (not to be confused with culling although often similar), various considerations on the *graphical working set* and its impact on performance, interactions between the proposed algorithm and others to improve rendering speed.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Although the algorithm introduced above covers a whole range of level of detail management techniques, real world applications usually employ specialized methods tailored to the information being rendered.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The first method, **discrete level of detail** (**DLOD**), involves creating multiple, discrete versions of the original geometry with decreased levels of geometric detail.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] At runtime, the full-detail models are substituted for the models with reduced detail as necessary.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Due to the discrete nature of the levels, there may be visual popping when one model is exchanged for another.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] This may be mitigated by alpha blending or morphing between states during the transition.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The second method, **continuous level of detail** (**CLOD**), uses a structure which contains a continuously variable spectrum of geometric detail.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The structure can then be probed to smoothly choose the appropriate level of detail required for the situation.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] A significant advantage of this technique is the ability to locally vary the detail; for instance, the side of a large object nearer to the view may be presented in high detail, while simultaneously reducing the detail on its distant side.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] In both cases, LODs are chosen based on some heuristic which is used to judge how much detail is being lost by the reduction in detail, such as by evaluation of the LOD's geometric error relative to the full-detail model.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Objects are then displayed with the minimum amount of detail required to satisfy the heuristic, which is designed to minimize geometric detail as much as possible to maximize performance while maintaining an acceptable level of visual quality.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The basic concept of discrete LOD (DLOD) is to provide various models to represent the same object.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Obtaining those models requires an external algorithm which is often non-trivial and subject of many polygon reduction techniques.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Successive LOD-ing algorithms will simply assume those models are available.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] DLOD algorithms are often used in performance-intensive applications with small data sets which can easily fit in memory.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Although out-of-core algorithms could be used, the information granularity is not well suited to this kind of application.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] This kind of algorithm is usually easier to get working, providing both faster performance and lower CPU usage because of the few operations involved.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] DLOD methods are often used for "stand-alone" moving objects, possibly including complex animation methods.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] A different approach is used for geomipmapping,[3] a popular terrain rendering algorithm because this applies to terrain meshes which are both graphically and topologically different from "object" meshes.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Instead of computing an error and simplify the mesh according to this, geomipmapping takes a fixed reduction method, evaluates the error introduced and computes a distance at which the error is acceptable.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Although straightforward, the algorithm provides decent performance.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] A discrete LOD approach would cache a certain number of models to be used at different distances.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Because the model can trivially be procedurally generated by its mathematical formulation, using a different number of sample points distributed on the surface is sufficient to generate the various models required.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] To simulate a realistic transform bound scenario, an ad-hoc written application can be used.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The use of simple algorithms and minimum fragment operations ensures that CPU bounding does not occur.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Each frame, the program will compute each sphere's distance and choose a model from a pool according to this information.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] To easily show the concept, the distance at which each model is used is hard coded in the source.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] A more involved method would compute adequate models according to the usage distance chosen.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] OpenGL is used for rendering due to its high efficiency in managing small batches, storing each model in a display list thus avoiding communication overheads.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Additional vertex load is given by applying two directional light sources ideally located infinitely far away.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The following table compares the performance of LOD aware rendering and a full detail (*brute force*) method.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Because hardware is geared towards large amounts of detail, rendering low polygon objects may score sub-optimal performances.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] HLOD avoids the problem by grouping different objects together[4].
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] This allows for higher efficiency as well as taking advantage of proximity considerations.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] LOD is especially useful in 3D video games.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Video game developers want to provide players with large worlds but are always constrained by hardware, frame rate and the real-time nature of video game graphics.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] With the advent of 3D games in the 1990s, a lot of video games simply did not render distant structures or objects.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Only nearby objects would be rendered and more distant parts would gradually fade, essentially implementing distance fog.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Video games using LOD rendering avoid this fog effect and can render larger areas.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Some notable early examples of LOD rendering in 3D video games include *The Killing Cloud*, *Spyro the Dragon*, *Crash Bandicoot: Warped*, *Unreal Tournament* and *Serious Sam: The First Encounter*.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Most modern 3D games use a combination of LOD rendering techniques, using different models for large structures and distance culling for environment details like grass and trees.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The effect is sometimes still noticeable, for example when the player character flies over the virtual terrain or uses a sniper scope for long distance viewing.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Especially grass and foliage will seem to pop-up when getting closer, also known as foliage culling.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] LOD can also be used to render fractal terrain in real time.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Unreal Engine 5's *Nanite* system essentially implements level-of-detail within meshes instead of just objects as a whole.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] LOD is found in GIS and 3D city models as a similar concept.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] It indicates how thoroughly real-world features have been mapped and how much the model adheres to its real-world counterpart.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Besides the geometric complexity, other metrics such as spatio-semantic coherence, resolution of the texture and attributes can be considered in the LOD of a model.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The standard CityGML contains one of the most prominent LOD categorizations.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The analogy of "LOD-ing" in GIS is referred to as generalization.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] In 3D computer graphics and solid modeling, a **polygon mesh** is a collection of **vertices**, **edges** and **faces** that define the shape of a polyhedral object's surface.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] It simplifies rendering, as in a wire-frame model.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] The faces usually consist of triangles (triangle mesh), quadrilaterals (quads), or other simple convex polygons (n-gons).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] A polygonal mesh may also be more generally composed of concave polygons, or even polygons with holes.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] The study of polygon meshes is a large sub-field of computer graphics (specifically 3D computer graphics) and geometric modeling.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Different representations of polygon meshes are used for different applications and goals.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] The variety of operations performed on meshes includes Boolean logic (Constructive solid geometry), smoothing, and simplification.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Algorithms also exist for ray tracing, collision detection, and rigid-body dynamics with polygon meshes.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] If the mesh's edges are rendered instead of the faces, then the model becomes a wireframe model.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Several methods exist for mesh generation, including the marching cubes algorithm.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Volumetric meshes are distinct from polygon meshes in that they explicitly represent both the surface and interior region of a structure, while polygon meshes only explicitly represent the surface (the volume is implicit).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Objects created with polygon meshes must store different types of elements.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] These include vertices, edges, faces, polygons and surfaces.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] In many applications, only vertices, edges and either faces or polygons are stored.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] A renderer may support only 3-sided faces, so polygons must be constructed of many of these, as shown above.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] However, many renderers either support quads and higher-sided polygons, or are able to convert polygons to triangles on the fly, making it unnecessary to store a mesh in a triangulated form.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] A vertex in computer graphics terms is a data structure that describes the position of a point in 2, 3 or 4D space on a surface along with optional attributes - other values used to render the object correctly.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Most attributes of a vertex represent vectors in the space to be rendered.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] These vectors are typically 2 (*x, y*) or 3 (*x, y, z*) dimensional and can include a fourth homogeneous coordinate (*w*)..
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] In real-time rendering these properties are used by a vertex shader or vertex pipeline.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Attributes can include position, color, reflectance, specularity, texture mapping coordinates, normal vectors, and displacement mapping.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Polygon meshes may be represented in a variety of ways, using different methods to store the vertex, edge and face data.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Each representation has advantages and disadvantages, discussed in Smith (2006).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Vertex-vertex meshes represent an object as a set of vertices connected to other vertices.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] This is the simplest representation, but not widely used since the face and edge information is implicit.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Thus, it is necessary to traverse the data in order to generate a list of faces for rendering.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] In addition, operations on edges and faces are not easily accomplished.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] However, VV meshes benefit from small storage space and efficient morphing of shape.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] The above figure shows a four-sided box as represented by a VV mesh.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Each vertex indexes its neighboring vertices.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] The last two vertices, 8 and 9 at the top and bottom center of the "box-cylinder", have four connected vertices rather than five.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] A general system must be able to handle an arbitrary number of vertices connected to any given vertex.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] For a complete description of VV meshes see Smith (2006).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Face-vertex meshes represent an object as a set of faces and a set of vertices.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] This is the most widely used mesh representation, being the input typically accepted by modern graphics hardware.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Face-vertex meshes improve on VV mesh for modelling in that they allow explicit lookup of the vertices of a face, and the faces surrounding a vertex.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] The above figure shows the "box-cylinder" example as an FV mesh.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Vertex v5 is highlighted to show the faces that surround it.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Notice that, in this example, every face is required to have exactly 3 vertices.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] However, this does not mean every vertex has the same number of surrounding faces.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] For rendering, the face list is usually transmitted to the GPU as a set of indices to vertices, and the vertices are sent as position/color/normal structures (in the figure, only position is given).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] This has the benefit that changes in shape, but not geometry, can be dynamically updated by simply resending the vertex data without updating the face connectivity.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Modelling requires easy traversal of all structures.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] With face-vertex meshes it is easy to find the vertices of a face.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Also, the vertex list contains a list of faces connected to each vertex.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Unlike VV meshes, both faces and vertices are explicit, so locating neighboring faces and vertices is constant time.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] However, the edges are implicit, so a search is still needed to find all the faces surrounding a given face.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Other dynamic operations, such as splitting or merging a face, are also difficult with face-vertex meshes.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Introduced by Baumgart in 1975, winged-edge meshes explicitly represent the vertices, faces, and edges of a mesh.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] This representation is widely used in modelling programs to provide the greatest flexibility in dynamically changing the mesh geometry, because split and merge operations can be done quickly.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Their primary drawback is large storage requirements and increased complexity due to maintaining many indices.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] A good discussion of implementation issues of Winged-edge meshes may be found in the book *Graphics Gems II*.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes address the issue of traversing from edge to edge, and providing an ordered set of faces around an edge.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] For any given edge, the number of outgoing edges may be arbitrary.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] To simplify this, winged-edge meshes provide only four, the nearest clockwise and counter-clockwise edges at each end.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] The other edges may be traversed incrementally.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] The information for each edge therefore resembles a butterfly, hence "winged-edge" meshes.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] The above figure shows the "box-cylinder" as a winged-edge mesh.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] The total data for an edge consists of 2 vertices (endpoints), 2 faces (on each side), and 4 edges (winged-edge).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Rendering of winged-edge meshes for graphics hardware requires generating a face index list, which is usually done only when the geometry changes.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes are ideally suited for dynamic geometry, such as subdivision surfaces and interactive modelling, since changes to the mesh can occur locally.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Traversal across the mesh, as might be needed for collision detection, can be accomplished efficiently.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes are not the only representation which allows for dynamic changes to geometry.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] A representation which combines winged-edge meshes and face-vertex meshes is the render dynamic mesh (RDM), which explicitly stores both, the vertices of a face and faces of a vertex (like FV meshes), and the faces and vertices of an edge (like winged-edge).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] RDM's require less storage space than standard winged-edge meshes, and can be directly rendered by graphics hardware since the face list contains an index of vertices.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] In addition, traversal from vertex to face is explicit (constant time), as is from face to vertex.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] RDM's do not require the four outgoing edges since these can be found by traversing from edge to face, then face to neighboring edge.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] RDM's benefit from the features of winged-edge meshes by allowing for geometry to be dynamically updated.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] See Tobler & Maierhofer (WSCG 2006) for more details.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] The notation *avg(V,V)* means the average number of vertices connected to a given vertex; *avg(E,V)* means the average number of edges connected to a given vertex, and *avg(F,V)* is the average number of faces connected to a given vertex.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] The notation "V → f1, f2, f3, ... → v1, v2, v3, ..." describes that a traversal across multiple elements is required to perform the operation.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] For example, to get "all vertices around a given vertex V" using the face-vertex mesh, it is necessary to first find the faces around the given vertex V using the vertex list.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Then, from those faces, use the face list to find the vertices around them.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes explicitly store nearly all information, and other operations always traverse to the edge first to get additional info.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Vertex-vertex meshes are the only representation that explicitly stores the neighboring vertices of a given vertex.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] As the mesh representations become more complex (from left to right in the summary), the amount of information explicitly stored increases.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] This gives more direct, constant time, access to traversal and topology of various elements but at the cost of increased overhead and space in maintaining indices properly.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] As a general rule, face-vertex meshes are used whenever an object must be rendered on graphics hardware that does not change geometry (connectivity), but may deform or morph shape (vertex positions) such as real-time rendering of static or morphing objects.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge or render dynamic meshes are used when the geometry changes, such as in interactive modeling packages or for computing subdivision surfaces.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Vertex-vertex meshes are ideal for efficient, complex changes in geometry or topology so long as hardware rendering is not of concern.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Streaming meshes store faces in an ordered, yet independent, way so that the mesh can be transmitted in pieces.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] The order of faces may be spatial, spectral, or based on other properties of the mesh.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Streaming meshes allow a very large mesh to be rendered even while it is still being loaded.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Progressive meshes transmit the vertex and face data with increasing levels of detail.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Unlike *streaming meshes*, progressive meshes give the overall shape of the entire object, but at a low level of detail.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Additional data, new edges and faces, progressively increase the detail of the mesh.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Normal meshes transmit progressive changes to a mesh as a set of normal displacements from a base mesh.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] With this technique, a series of textures represent the desired incremental modifications.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Normal meshes are compact, since only a single scalar value is needed to express displacement.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] However, the technique requires a complex series of transformations to create the displacement textures.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] There exist many different file formats for storing polygon mesh data.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Each format is most effective when used for the purpose intended by its creator.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/polygon-mesh] Popular formats include .fbx, .dae, .obj, and .stl.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] In vector computer graphics, CAD systems, and geographic information systems, a **geometric primitive** (or **prim**) is the simplest (i.e.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] 'atomic' or irreducible) geometric shape that the system can handle (draw, store).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] Sometimes the subroutines that draw the corresponding objects are called "geometric primitives" as well.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] The most "primitive" primitives are point and straight line segments, which were all that early vector graphics systems had.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] In constructive solid geometry, primitives are simple geometric shapes such as a cube, cylinder, sphere, cone, pyramid, torus.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] Modern 2D computer graphics systems may operate with primitives which are curves (segments of straight lines, circles and more complicated curves), as well as shapes (boxes, arbitrary polygons, circles).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] A common set of two-dimensional primitives includes lines, points, and polygons, although some people prefer to consider triangles primitives, because every polygon can be constructed from triangles (polygon triangulation).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] All other graphic elements are built up from these primitives.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] In three dimensions, triangles or polygons positioned in three-dimensional space can be used as primitives to model more complex 3D forms.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] In some cases, curves (such as Bézier curves, circles, etc.) may be considered primitives; in other cases, curves are complex forms created from many straight, primitive shapes.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] In GIS, the terrain surface is often spoken of colloquially as "2 1/2 dimensional," because only the upper surface needs to be represented.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] Thus, elevation can be conceptualized as a scalar field property or function of two-dimensional space, affording it a number of data modeling efficiencies over true 3-dimensional objects.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] A shape of any of these dimensions greater than zero consists of an infinite number of distinct points.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] Because digital systems are finite, only a sample set of the points in a shape can be stored.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] Thus, vector data structures typically represent geometric primitives using a strategic sample, organized in structures that facilitate the software interpolating the remainder of the shape at the time of analysis or display, using the algorithms of Computational geometry.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] A wide variety of vector data structures and formats have been developed during the history of Geographic information systems, but they share a fundamental basis of storing a core set of geometric primitives to represent the location and extent of geographic phenomena.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] Locations of points are almost always measured within a standard Earth-based coordinate system, whether the spherical Geographic coordinate system (latitude/longitude), or a planar coordinate system, such as the Universal Transverse Mercator.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] They also share the need to store a set of attributes of each geographic feature alongside its shape; traditionally, this has been accomplished using the data models, data formats, and even software of relational databases.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] Early vector formats, such as POLYVRT, the ARC/INFO Coverage, and the Esri shapefile support a basic set of geometric primitives: points, polylines, and polygons, only in two dimensional space and the latter two with only straight line interpolation.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] TIN data structures for representing terrain surfaces as triangle meshes were also added.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] Since the mid 1990s, new formats have been developed that extend the range of available primitives, generally standardized by the Open Geospatial Consortium's Simple Features specification.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] Frequently, a representation of the shape of a real-world phenomenon may have a different (usually lower) dimension than the phenomenon being represented.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] For example, a city (a two-dimensional region) may be represented as a point, or a road (a three-dimensional volume of material) may be represented as a line.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] This dimensional generalization correlates with tendencies in spatial cognition.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] For example, asking the distance between two cities presumes a conceptual model of the cities as points, while giving directions involving travel "up," "down," or "along" a road imply a one-dimensional conceptual model.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] In CAD software or 3D modelling, the interface may present the user with the ability to create primitives which may be further modified by edits.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] For example, in the practice of box modelling the user will start with a cuboid, then use extrusion and other operations to create the model.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] In this use the primitive is just a convenient starting point, rather than the fundamental unit of modelling.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] A 3D package may also include a list of extended primitives which are more complex shapes that come with the package.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] For example, a teapot is listed as a primitive in 3D Studio Max.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] Various graphics accelerators exist with hardware acceleration for rendering specific primitives such as lines or triangles, frequently with texture mapping and shaders.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/primitive-geometry] Modern 3D accelerators typically accept sequences of triangles as triangle strips.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rasterisation] In computer graphics, **rasterisation** (British English) or **rasterization** (American English) is the task of taking an image described in a vector graphics format (shapes) and converting it into a raster image which represents the original image.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rasterisation] The rasterized image may then be displayed on a computer display, video display or printer, or stored in a bitmap file format.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rasterisation] Rasterization may refer to the technique of drawing 3D models, or to the conversion of 2D rendering primitives, such as polygons and line segments, into a rasterized format.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rasterisation] The term "rasterisation" comes from German *Raster* 'grid, pattern, schema' and Latin *rāstrum* 'scraper, rake'.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rasterisation] Bresenham's line algorithm is an example of an algorithm used to rasterize lines.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rasterisation] Algorithms such as the midpoint circle algorithm are used to render circles onto a pixelated canvas.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rasterisation] Polygons are a common representation of digital 3D models.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rasterisation] Before rasterization, individual polygons are triangulated - therefore, a typical problem to solve in 3D rasterization is rasterization of a triangle.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rasterisation] 2. no pixel is rasterized more than once, i.e. the rasterized triangles don't overlap.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rasterisation] This is to guarantee that the result doesn't depend on the order in which the triangles are rasterized.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rasterisation] Overdrawing pixels can also mean wasting computing power on pixels that would be overwritten.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rasterisation] This leads to establishing **rasterization rules** to guarantee the above conditions.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rasterisation] 2. its center lies exactly on the triangle edge (or multiple edges in case of corners) – that is (or, in case of corners, all are), either the *top* or *left* edge.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rasterisation] A *top* edge is an edge that is exactly horizontal and lies above other edges, and a *left* edge is a non-horizontal edge that is on the left side of the triangle.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rasterisation] This rule decides which triangle a pixel on a boundary belongs to.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rasterisation] It is implemented by Direct3D and OpenGL (although the specification here only requires a consistent rule).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rasterisation] Rasterization is one of the typical techniques of rendering 3D models.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rasterisation] Compared with other rendering techniques such as ray tracing, rasterization is extremely fast and therefore used in most realtime 3D engines.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rasterisation] However, rasterization is simply the process of computing the mapping from scene geometry to pixels and does not prescribe a particular way to compute the color of those pixels.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rasterisation] The specific color of each pixel is assigned by a pixel shader (which in modern GPUs is completely programmable).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rasterisation] Shading may take into account physical effects such as light position, their approximations or purely artistic intent.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rasterisation] The process of rasterizing 3D models onto a 2D plane for display on a computer screen ("screen space") is often carried out by fixed function (non-programmable) hardware within the graphics pipeline.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rasterisation] This is because there is no motivation for modifying the techniques for rasterization used at render time and a special-purpose system allows for high efficiency.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rasterisation] The quality of rasterization can be improved by antialiasing, which creates "smooth" edges.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rasterisation] Sub-pixel precision is a method which takes into account positions on a finer scale than the pixel grid and can produce different results even if the endpoints of a primitive fall into same pixel coordinates, producing smoother movement animations.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rasterisation] Simple or older hardware, such as PlayStation 1, lacked sub-pixel precision in 3D rasterization.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In a computer graphics context, in standard usage, the word "rendering" by itself means rendering 3D scenes, but it is sometimes used with a broader meaning.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A modifier such as "2D" or "3D" is used when there is potential ambiguity (e.g.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A software application or component that performs rendering is called a **rendering engine**, **render engine**, **rendering system**, **graphics engine**, or simply a **renderer**.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A distinction is made between real-time rendering, in which images are generated and displayed immediately (ideally fast enough to give the impression of motion or animation), and offline rendering (sometimes called pre-rendering) in which images or film frames, are generated for later viewing.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Offline rendering can use a slower and higher-quality renderer.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Interactive applications such as games must primarily use real-time rendering, although they may incorporate pre-rendered content.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rendering produces images of scenes or objects defined using coordinates in 3D space, seen from a particular viewpoint.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] It uses knowledge and ideas from optics, the study of visual perception, mathematics, and software engineering, and it has applications such as video games, simulators, visual effects for films and television, design visualization, and medical diagnosis.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Realistic rendering requires modeling the propagation of light in an environment, e.g. by applying the rendering equation.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Real-time rendering uses high-performance *rasterization* algorithms that process a list of shapes and determine which pixels are covered by each shape.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When more realism is required (e.g. for architectural visualization or visual effects) slower pixel-by-pixel algorithms such as *ray tracing* are used instead.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] (Ray tracing can also be used selectively during rasterized rendering to improve the realism of lighting and reflections.) A type of ray tracing called *path tracing* is currently the most common technique for photorealistic rendering.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Path tracing is also popular for generating high-quality non-photorealistic images, such as frames for 3D animated films.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Both rasterization and ray tracing can be sped up ("accelerated") by specially designed microprocessors called GPUs.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rasterization algorithms are also used to produce images containing only 2D shapes such as polygons and text.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] This type of rendering is sometimes called *2D rendering*, and its applications include digital illustration, graphic design, 2D animation, desktop publishing and the display of user interfaces.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Historically, rendering was called **image synthesis** but today this term is likely to mean AI image generation.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The term "neural rendering" is sometimes used when a neural network is the primary means of generating an image but some degree of control over the output image is provided.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Neural networks can also assist rendering without replacing traditional algorithms, e.g. by removing noise from path traced images.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A large proportion of computer graphics research has worked towards producing images that resemble photographs.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Fundamental techniques that make this possible were invented in the 1980s, but at the end of the decade, photorealism for complex scenes was still considered a distant goal.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Today, photorealism is routinely achievable for offline rendering, but remains difficult for real-time rendering.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In order to produce realistic images, rendering must simulate how light travels from light sources, is reflected, refracted, and scattered (often many times) by objects in the scene, passes through a camera lens, and finally reaches the film or sensor of the camera.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The physics used in these simulations is primarily geometrical optics, in which particles of light follow (usually straight) lines called *rays*, but in some situations (such as when rendering thin films, like the surface of soap bubbles) the wave nature of light must be taken into account.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In realistic scenes, objects are illuminated both by light that arrives directly from a light source (after passing mostly unimpeded through air), and light that has bounced off other objects in the scene.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The simulation of this complex lighting is called global illumination.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In the past, indirect lighting was often faked (especially when rendering animated films) by placing additional hidden lights in the scene, but today path tracing is used to render it accurately.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] For true photorealism, the camera used to take the photograph must be simulated.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The *thin lens approximation* allows combining perspective projection with depth of field (and bokeh) emulation.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Camera lens simulations can be made more realistic by modeling the way light is refracted by the components of the lens.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Motion blur is often simulated if film or video frames are being rendered.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Simulated lens flare and bloom are sometimes added to make the image appear subjectively brighter (although the design of real cameras tries to reduce these effects).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Realistic rendering uses mathematical descriptions of how different surface materials reflect light, called *reflectance models* or (when physically plausible) *bidirectional reflectance distribution functions (BRDFs)*.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rendering materials such as marble, plant leaves, and human skin requires simulating an effect called subsurface scattering, in which a portion of the light travels into the material, is scattered, and then travels back out again.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The way color, and properties such as roughness, vary over a surface can be represented efficiently using texture mapping.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] For some applications (including early stages of 3D modeling), simplified rendering styles such as wireframe rendering may be appropriate, particularly when the material and surface details have not been defined and only the shape of an object is known.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Games and other real-time applications may use simpler and less realistic rendering techniques as an artistic or design choice, or to allow higher frame rates on lower-end hardware.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Orthographic and isometric projections can be used for a stylized effect or to ensure that parallel lines are depicted as parallel in CAD rendering.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Non-photorealistic rendering (NPR) uses techniques like edge detection and posterization to produce 3D images that resemble technical illustrations, cartoons, or other styles of drawing or painting.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In 2D computer graphics the positions and sizes of shapes are specified using 2D coordinates (x and y) instead of 3D coordinates (x, y, and z).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering APIs often use a resolution-independent coordinate system, with a viewport determining how to convert coordinates to pixel indexes called *device coordinates*.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Transformations such as scaling, translation, and rotation may be applied before rendering the shapes.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These affine transformations are often represented by 3 × 3 matrices, allowing easier composition of transformations.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Higher-quality 2D rendering engines such as SVG renderers usually implement anti-aliasing to reduce the jagged appearance of rasterized lines and shape edges.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When rendering overlapping shapes, renderers commonly use a "painter's model" in which the shapes are drawn in some determined order, or their contributions to each pixel are composited using blending operations that may depend on the order of the inputs.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Renderers may allow giving shapes a "z index" or "stacking order" to specify the rendering or blending order (unlike the z coordinate used in 3D rendering, this third coordinate only indicates an order, not a distance, and cannot be meaningfully rotated together with the x and y coordinates).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering typically does not simulate light propagation (which would likely require specifying 3D positions or thickness for the shapes).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Effects such as drop shadows and transparency are defined by mathematical functions with no physical basis.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering for print output may need to support very high resolutions, e.g.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 600 or 1200 DPI for a typical laser printer, or 2400 DPI or higher for an imagesetter or platesetter.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Grayscale and color images require halftones (or some form of dithering or stochastic screening) and color separations.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A rendering engine called a *raster image processor* (RIP) converts input data such as PDF files into the high-resolution bitmap images used by the printer.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Before a 3D scene or 2D image can be rendered, it must be described in a way that the rendering software can understand.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Historically, inputs for both 2D and 3D rendering were usually text files, which are easier than binary files for humans to edit and debug.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Traditional rendering algorithms use geometric descriptions of 3D scenes or 2D images.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Applications and algorithms that render visualizations of data scanned from the real world, or scientific simulations, may require different types of input data.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The PostScript format (which is often credited with the rise of desktop publishing) provides a standardized, interoperable way to describe 2D graphics and page layout.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The Scalable Vector Graphics (SVG) format is also text-based, and the PDF format uses the PostScript language internally.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Many file formats exist for storing individual 3D objects or "models".
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These can be imported into a larger scene, or loaded on-demand by rendering software or games.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A realistic scene may require hundreds of items like household objects, vehicles, and trees, and 3D artists often utilize large libraries of models.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In game production, these models (along with other data such as textures, audio files, and animations) are referred to as "assets".
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Scientific and engineering visualization often requires rendering volumetric data generated by 3D scans or simulations.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Perhaps the most common source of such data is medical CT and MRI scans, which need to be rendered for diagnosis.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Volumetric data can be extremely large, and requires specialized data formats to store it efficiently, particularly if the volume is *sparse* (with empty regions that do not contain data).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Before rendering, level sets for volumetric data can be extracted and converted into a mesh of triangles, e.g. by using the marching cubes algorithm.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Algorithms have also been developed that work directly with volumetric data, for example to render realistic depictions of the way light is scattered and absorbed by clouds and smoke, and this type of volumetric rendering is used extensively in visual effects for movies.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When rendering lower-resolution volumetric data without interpolation, the individual cubes or "voxels" may be visible, an effect sometimes used deliberately for game graphics.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Photographs of real world objects can be incorporated into a rendered scene by using them as textures for 3D objects.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Photos of a scene can also be stitched together to create panoramic images or environment maps, which allow the scene to be rendered very efficiently but only from a single viewpoint.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Scanning of real objects and scenes using structured light or lidar produces point clouds consisting of the coordinates of millions of individual points in space, sometimes along with color information.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These point clouds may either be rendered directly or converted into meshes before rendering.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A more recent, experimental approach is description of scenes using radiance fields which define the color, intensity, and direction of incoming light at each point in space.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] (This is conceptually similar to, but not identical to, the light field recorded by a hologram.) For any useful resolution, the amount of data in a radiance field is so large that it is impractical to represent it directly as volumetric data, and an approximation function must be found.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Neural networks are typically used to generate and evaluate these approximations, sometimes using video frames, or a collection of photographs of a scene taken at different angles, as "training data".
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Algorithms related to neural networks have recently been used to find approximations of a scene as 3D Gaussians.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The resulting representation is similar to a point cloud, except that it uses fuzzy, partially-transparent blobs of varying dimensions and orientations instead of points.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] As with neural radiance fields, these approximations are often generated from photographs or video frames.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The output of rendering may be displayed immediately on the screen (many times a second, in the case of real-time rendering such as games) or saved in a raster graphics file format such as JPEG or PNG.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] High-end rendering applications commonly use the OpenEXR file format, which can represent finer gradations of colors and high dynamic range lighting, allowing tone mapping or other adjustments to be applied afterwards without loss of quality.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The output of a renderer sometimes includes more than just RGB color values.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Transparency information can be included, allowing rendered foreground objects to be composited with photographs or video.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] It is also sometimes useful to store the contributions of different lights, or of specular and diffuse lighting, as separate channels, so lighting can be adjusted after rendering.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The OpenEXR format allows storing many channels of data in a single file.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Renderers such as Blender and Pixar RenderMan support a large variety of configurable values called Arbitrary Output Variables (AOVs).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Choosing how to render a 3D scene usually involves trade-offs between speed, memory usage, and realism (although realism is not always desired).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The **algorithms** developed over the years follow a loose progression, with more advanced methods becoming practical as computing power and memory capacity increased.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Multiple techniques may be used for a single final image.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important distinction is between image order algorithms, which iterate over pixels in the image, and object order algorithms, which iterate over objects in the scene.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For simple scenes, object order is usually more efficient, as there are fewer objects than pixels.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] algorithms that also support filled shapes.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In principle, any 2D vector graphics renderer can be used to render 3D objects by first projecting them onto a 2D image plane.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Different realistic or stylized effects can be obtained by coloring the pixels covered by the objects in different ways.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rasterization is usually synonymous with "object order" rendering (as described above).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It can be used to implement "image order" rendering by casting a ray for each pixel, and finding a corresponding point in the scene.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] , requiring a varying number of ray casting operations for each path.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] is usually in the domain of path tracing.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] approach that breaks surfaces in the scene into pieces, and estimates the amount of light that each piece receives from light sources, or indirectly from other surfaces.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] of each surface is known, the scene can be rendered using rasterization or ray tracing.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] , giving ray tracing a rigorous mathematical foundation.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Each of the above approaches has many variations, and there is some overlap.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Path tracing may be considered either a distinct technique or a particular type of ray tracing.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Note that the usage of terminology related to ray tracing and path tracing has changed significantly over time.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray marching is a family of algorithms, used by ray casting, for finding intersections between a ray and a complex object, such as a volumetric dataset or a surface defined by a signed distance function.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It is not, by itself, a rendering method, but it can be incorporated into ray tracing and path tracing, and is used by rasterization to implement screen-space reflection and other effects.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A technique called photon mapping traces paths of photons from a light source to an object, accumulating data about irradiance which is then used during conventional ray tracing or path tracing.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering a scene using only rays traced from the light source to the camera is impractical, even though it corresponds more closely to reality, because a huge number of photons would need to be simulated, only a tiny fraction of which actually hit the camera.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Some authors call conventional ray tracing "backward" ray tracing because it traces the paths of photons backwards from the camera to the light source, and call following paths from the light source (as in photon mapping) "forward" ray tracing.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However, sometimes the meaning of these terms is reversed.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Tracing rays starting at the light source can also be called *particle tracing* or *light tracing*, which avoids this ambiguity.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Real-time rendering, including video game graphics, typically uses rasterization, but increasingly combines it with ray tracing and path tracing.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] To enable realistic global illumination, real-time rendering often relies on pre-rendered ("baked") lighting for stationary objects.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For moving objects, it may use a technique called *light probes*, in which lighting is recorded by rendering omnidirectional views of the scene at chosen points in space (often points on a grid to allow easier interpolation).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These are similar to environment maps, but typically use a very low resolution or an approximation such as spherical harmonics.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The term *rasterization* (in a broad sense) encompasses many techniques used for 2D rendering and real-time 3D rendering.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] 3D animated films were rendered by rasterization before ray tracing and path tracing became practical.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A renderer combines rasterization with *geometry processing* (which is not specific to rasterization) and *pixel processing* which computes the RGB color values to be placed in the *framebuffer* for display.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Historically, 3D rasterization used algorithms like the *Warnock algorithm* and *scanline rendering* (also called "scan-conversion"), which can handle arbitrary polygons and can rasterize many shapes simultaneously.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Although such algorithms are still important for 2D rendering, 3D rendering now usually divides shapes into triangles and rasterizes them individually using simpler methods.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] High-performance algorithms exist for rasterizing 2D lines, including anti-aliased lines, as well as ellipses and filled triangles.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important special case of 2D rasterization is text rendering, which requires careful anti-aliasing and rounding of coordinates to avoid distorting the letterforms and preserve spacing, density, and sharpness.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] After 3D coordinates have been projected onto the image plane, rasterization is primarily a 2D problem, but the 3rd dimension necessitates *hidden surface removal*.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early computer graphics used geometric algorithms or ray casting to remove the hidden portions of shapes, or used the *painter's algorithm*, which sorts shapes by depth (distance from camera) and renders them from back to front.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Depth sorting was later avoided by incorporating depth comparison into the scanline rendering algorithm.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The *z-buffer* algorithm performs the comparisons indirectly by including a depth or "z" value in the framebuffer.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A pixel is only covered by a shape if that shape's z value is lower (indicating closer to the camera) than the z value currently in the buffer.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The z-buffer requires additional memory (an expensive resource at the time it was invented) but simplifies the rasterization code and permits multiple passes.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Memory is now faster and more plentiful, and a z-buffer is almost always used for real-time rendering.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A drawback of the basic z-buffer algorithm is that each pixel ends up either entirely covered by a single object or filled with the background color, causing jagged edges in the final image.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early *anti-aliasing* approaches addressed this by detecting when a pixel is partially covered by a shape, and calculating the covered area.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The A-buffer (and other supersampling and multi-sampling techniques) solve the problem less precisely but with higher performance.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For real-time 3D graphics, it has become common to use complicated heuristics (and even neural-networks) to perform anti-aliasing.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In 3D rasterization, color is usually determined by a *pixel shader* or *fragment shader*, a small program that is run for each pixel.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Until relatively recently, Pixar used rasterization for rendering its animated films.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Unlike the renderers commonly used for real-time graphics, the Reyes rendering system in Pixar's RenderMan software was optimized for rendering very small (pixel-sized) polygons, and incorporated stochastic sampling techniques more typically associated with ray tracing.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] One of the simplest ways to render a 3D scene is to test if a ray starting at the viewpoint (the "eye" or "camera") intersects any of the geometric shapes in the scene, repeating this test using a different ray direction for each pixel.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This method, called *ray casting*, was important in early computer graphics, and is a fundamental building block for more advanced algorithms.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray casting can be used to render shapes defined by *constructive solid geometry* (CSG) operations.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early ray casting experiments include the work of Arthur Appel in the 1960s.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Appel rendered shadows by casting an additional ray from each visible surface point towards a light source.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] He also tried rendering the density of illumination by casting random rays from the light source towards the object and plotting the intersection points (similar to the later technique called *photon mapping*).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When rendering scenes containing many objects, testing the intersection of a ray with every object becomes very expensive.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Special data structures are used to speed up this process by allowing large numbers of objects to be excluded quickly (such as objects behind the camera).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These structures are analogous to database indexes for finding the relevant objects.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The most common are the *bounding volume hierarchy* (BVH), which stores a pre-computed bounding box or sphere for each branch of a tree of objects, and the *k-d tree* which recursively divides space into two parts.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent GPUs include hardware acceleration for BVH intersection tests.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] K-d trees are a special case of *binary space partitioning*, which was frequently used in early computer graphics (it can also generate a rasterization order for the painter's algorithm).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Octrees*, another historically popular technique, are still often used for volumetric data.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Geometric formulas are sufficient for finding the intersection of a ray with shapes like spheres, polygons, and polyhedra, but for most curved surfaces there is no analytic solution, or the intersection is difficult to compute accurately using limited precision floating point numbers.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Root-finding algorithms such as Newton's method can sometimes be used.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] To avoid these complications, curved surfaces are often approximated as meshes of triangles.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Volume rendering (e.g. rendering clouds and smoke), and some surfaces such as fractals, may require ray marching instead of basic ray casting.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray casting can be used to render an image by tracing light rays backwards from a simulated camera.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] After finding a point on a surface where a ray originated, another ray is traced towards the light source to determine if anything is casting a shadow on that point.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If there are multiple light sources, brightness contributions of the lights are added together.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For color images, calculations are repeated for multiple wavelengths of light (e.g. red, green, and blue).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing usually performs anti-aliasing by taking the average of multiple samples for each pixel.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It may also use multiple samples for effects like depth of field and motion blur.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If evenly spaced ray directions or times are used for each of these features, many rays are required, and some aliasing will remain.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Cook-style*, *stochastic*, or *Monte Carlo ray tracing* avoids this problem by using random sampling instead of evenly spaced samples.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This type of ray tracing is commonly called *distributed ray tracing*, or *distribution ray tracing* because it samples rays from probability distributions.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Distribution ray tracing can also render realistic "soft" shadows from large lights by using a random sample of points on the light when testing for shadowing, and it can simulate chromatic aberration by sampling multiple wavelengths from the spectrum of light.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Real surface materials reflect small amounts of light in almost every direction because they have small (or microscopic) bumps and grooves.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A distribution ray tracer can simulate this by sampling possible ray directions, which allows rendering blurry reflections from glossy and metallic surfaces.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However, if this procedure is repeated recursively to simulate realistic indirect lighting, and if more than one sample is taken at each surface point, the tree of rays quickly becomes huge.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Another kind of ray tracing, called *path tracing*, handles indirect light more efficiently, avoiding branching, and ensures that the distribution of all possible paths from a light source to the camera is sampled in an unbiased way.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing was often used for rendering reflections in animated films, until path tracing became standard for film rendering.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Films such as Shrek 2 and Monsters University also used distribution ray tracing or path tracing to precompute indirect illumination for a scene or frame prior to rendering it using rasterization.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Advances in GPU technology have made real-time ray tracing possible in games, although it is currently almost always used in combination with rasterization.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This enables visual effects that are difficult with only rasterization, including reflection from curved surfaces and interreflective objects, and shadows that are accurate over a wide range of distances and surface orientations.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing support is included in recent versions of the graphics APIs used by games, such as DirectX, Metal, and Vulkan.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing has been used to render simulated black holes, and the appearance of objects moving at close to the speed of light, by taking spacetime curvature and relativistic effects into account during light ray simulation.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Radiosity (named after the radiometric quantity of the same name) is a method for rendering objects illuminated by light bouncing off rough or matte surfaces.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This type of illumination is called *indirect light*, *environment lighting*, *diffuse lighting*, or *diffuse interreflection*, and the problem of rendering it realistically is called *global illumination*.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rasterization and basic forms of ray tracing (other than distribution ray tracing and path tracing) can only roughly approximate indirect light, e.g. by adding a uniform "ambient" lighting amount chosen by the artist.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Radiosity techniques are also suited to rendering scenes with *area lights* such as rectangular fluorescent lighting panels, which are difficult for rasterization and traditional ray tracing.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In the original radiosity method (first proposed in 1984) now called *classical radiosity*, surfaces and lights in the scene are split into pieces called *patches*, a process called *meshing* (this step makes it a finite element method).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The rendering code must then determine what fraction of the light being emitted or diffusely reflected (scattered) by each patch is received by each other patch.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These fractions are called *form factors* or *view factors* (first used in engineering to model radiative heat transfer).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The form factors are multiplied by the albedo of the receiving surface and put in a matrix.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The lighting in the scene can then be expressed as a matrix equation (or equivalently a system of linear equations) that can be solved by methods from linear algebra.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Solving the radiosity equation gives the total amount of light emitted and reflected by each patch, which is divided by area to get a value called *radiosity* that can be used when rasterizing or ray tracing to determine the color of pixels corresponding to visible parts of the patch.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For real-time rendering, this value (or more commonly the irradiance, which does not depend on local surface albedo) can be pre-computed and stored in a texture (called an *irradiance map*) or stored as vertex data for 3D models.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This feature was used in architectural visualization software to allow real-time walk-throughs of a building interior after computing the lighting.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The large size of the matrices used in classical radiosity (the square of the number of patches) causes problems for realistic scenes.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Practical implementations may use Jacobi or Gauss-Seidel iterations, which is equivalent (at least in the Jacobi case) to simulating the propagation of light one bounce at a time until the amount of light remaining (not yet absorbed by surfaces) is insignificant.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Form factors may be recomputed when they are needed, to avoid storing a complete matrix in memory.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The quality of rendering is often determined by the size of the patches, e.g. very fine meshes are needed to depict the edges of shadows accurately.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important improvement is *hierarchical radiosity*, which uses a coarser mesh (larger patches) for simulating the transfer of light between surfaces that are far away from one another, and adaptively sub-divides the patches as needed.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This allows radiosity to be used for much larger and more complex scenes.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Alternative and extended versions of the radiosity method support non-Lambertian surfaces, such as glossy surfaces and mirrors, and sometimes use volumes or "clusters" of objects as well as surface patches.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Simplified and partially precomputed versions of radiosity are widely used for real-time rendering, combined with techniques such as *octree radiosity* that store approximations of the light field.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As part of the approach known as *physically based rendering*, **path tracing** has become the dominant technique for rendering realistic scenes, including effects for movies.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For example, the popular open source 3D software Blender uses path tracing in its Cycles renderer.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Like *distributed ray tracing*, path tracing is a kind of *stochastic* or *randomized* ray tracing that uses Monte Carlo or Quasi-Monte Carlo integration.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It was proposed and named in 1986 by Jim Kajiya in the same paper as the rendering equation.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Kajiya suggested reducing the noise present in the output images by using *stratified sampling* and *importance sampling* for making random decisions such as choosing which ray to follow at each step of a path.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Even with these techniques, path tracing would not have been practical for film rendering, using computers available at the time, because the computational cost of generating enough samples to reduce variance to an acceptable level was too high.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Monster House, the first feature film rendered entirely using path tracing, was not released until 20 years later.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In its basic form, path tracing is inefficient (requiring too many samples) for rendering caustics and scenes where light enters indirectly through narrow spaces.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Attempts were made to address these weaknesses in the 1990s.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Metropolis light transport* samples paths by modifying paths that were previously traced, spending more time exploring paths that are similar to other "bright" paths, which increases the chance of discovering even brighter paths.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Multiple importance sampling* provides a way to reduce variance when combining samples from more than one sampling method, particularly when some samples are much noisier than the others.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This later work was summarized and expanded upon in Eric Veach's 1997 PhD thesis, which helped raise interest in path tracing in the computer graphics community.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The Arnold renderer, first released in 1998, proved that path tracing was practical for rendering frames for films, and that there was a demand for unbiased and physically based rendering in the film industry; other commercial and open source path tracing renderers began appearing.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Computational cost was addressed by rapid advances in CPU and cluster performance.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Path tracing's relative simplicity and its nature as a Monte Carlo method (sampling hundreds or thousands of paths per pixel) have made it attractive to implement on a GPU, especially on recent GPUs that support ray tracing acceleration technology such as Nvidia's RTX and OptiX.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However bidirectional path tracing and Metropolis light transport are more difficult to implement efficiently on a GPU.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Techniques have been developed to denoise the output of path tracing, reducing the number of paths required to achieve acceptable quality, at the risk of losing some detail or introducing small-scale artifacts that are more objectionable than noise.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural networks are now widely used for this purpose.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Research into improving path tracing continues.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Many variations of bidirectional path tracing and Metropolis light transport have been explored, and ways of combining path tracing with photon mapping.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent *path guiding* approaches construct approximations of the light field probability distribution in each volume of space, so paths can be sampled more effectively.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] By combining denoising and hardware ray tracing acceleration, it is now practical to use path tracing for real-time rendering.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Due to performance constraints, biased techniques such as a radiance cache may be incorporated.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Spatiotemporal reservoir resampling (ReSTIR) aims to improve the quality of real-time path tracing and allow more complex lighting by reusing samples (paths) from previous frames and adjacent pixels.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As of 2003, machine learning (ML) techniques were being used in other areas of computer graphics, such as texture synthesis, fitting surfaces to point clouds, and fitting curves to motion capture data.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The use of ML for rendering expanded with the availability of GPUs that can evaluate neural networks (especially convolutional neural networks) quickly.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural networks and Gaussian mixture models have been used in conjunction with rendering techniques such as path tracing to encode bidirectional reflectance distribution functions (BRDFs), or to encode cached radiance at points in space (for biased acceleration of rendering or for path guiding).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural radiance fields (NeRFs) take the latter approach to an extreme, encoding radiance at all points in a volume, and using evaluation of this approximation as the primary rendering method.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] One of the most widely used applications of machine learning in rendering is denoising of path traced images (in practice, most path tracing now likely uses such a denoiser).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Denoisers specialized for real-time rendering can work with very low sample counts and improve temporal coherence to reduce flickering.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering is usually limited by available computing power and memory bandwidth, and so specialized hardware has been developed to speed it up ("accelerate" it), particularly for real-time rendering.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Hardware features such as a framebuffer for raster graphics are required to display the output of rendering smoothly in real time.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Hardware acceleration does not replace the use of software for rendering, rather it speeds up selected operations or calculations using dedicated circuits, or runs portions of the software's code on a different type of processor.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In the era of vector monitors (also called *calligraphic displays*), a display processing unit (DPU) was a dedicated CPU or coprocessor that maintained a list of visual elements and redrew them continuously on the screen by controlling an electron beam.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Advanced DPUs such as Evans & Sutherland's Line Drawing System-1 (and later models produced into the 1980s) incorporated 3D coordinate transformation features to accelerate rendering of wire-frame images.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Evans & Sutherland also made the Digistar planetarium projection system, which was a vector display that could render both stars and wire-frame graphics (the vector-based Digistar and Digistar II were used in many planetariums, and a few may still be in operation).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A Digistar prototype was used for rendering 3D star fields for the film Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan – some of the first 3D computer graphics sequences ever seen in a feature film.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Shaded 3D graphics rendering in the 1970s and early 1980s was usually implemented on general-purpose computers, such as the PDP-10 used by researchers at the University of Utah.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It was difficult to speed up using specialized hardware because it involves a pipeline of complex steps, requiring data addressing, decision-making, and computation capabilities typically only provided by CPUs (although dedicated circuits for speeding up particular operations were proposed ).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Supercomputers or specially designed multi-CPU computers or clusters were sometimes used for ray tracing.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Clark and Marc Hannah designed the Geometry Engine, a VLSI chip for performing some of the steps of the 3D rasterization pipeline, and started the company Silicon Graphics (SGI) to commercialize this technology.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Home computers and game consoles in the 1980s contained graphics coprocessors that were capable of scrolling and filling areas of the display, and drawing sprites and lines, though they were not useful for rendering realistic images.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Towards the end of the 1980s PC graphics cards and arcade games with 3D rendering acceleration began to appear, and in the 1990s such technology became commonplace.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Today, even low-power mobile processors typically incorporate 3D graphics acceleration features.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The 3D graphics accelerators of the 1990s evolved into modern GPUs.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] GPUs are general-purpose processors, like CPUs, but they are designed for tasks that can be broken into many small, similar, mostly independent sub-tasks (such as rendering individual pixels) and performed in parallel.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Due to their origins, GPUs typically still provide specialized hardware acceleration for some steps of a traditional 3D rasterization pipeline, including hidden surface removal using a z-buffer, and texture mapping with mipmaps, but these features are no longer always used.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent GPUs have features to accelerate finding the intersections of rays with a bounding volume hierarchy, to help speed up all variants of ray tracing and path tracing, as well as neural network acceleration features sometimes useful for rendering.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering algorithms will run efficiently on a GPU only if they can be implemented using small groups of threads that perform mostly the same operations.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As an example of code that meets this requirement: when rendering a small square of pixels in a simple ray-traced image, all threads will likely be intersecting rays with the same object and performing the same lighting computations.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For performance and architectural reasons, GPUs run groups of around 16-64 threads called *warps* or *wavefronts* in lock-step (all threads in the group are executing the same instructions at the same time).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If not all threads in the group need to run particular blocks of code (due to conditions) then some threads will be idle, or the results of their computations will be discarded, causing degraded performance.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Historically, the term *hardware rendering* (possibly an abbreviation of "hardware accelerated rendering" or "hardware-assisted rendering") was sometimes used to mean rendering using a hardware-accelerated rasterization pipeline (typically for real-time rendering).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In contrast, *software rendering* meant offline rendering using software that was not limited by the capabilities of graphics hardware, and could use more realistic and higher quality techniques.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Both hardware and software have evolved, and although these terms are still used, their meaning may now be context-dependent.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When OpenGL and Direct3D were introduced in the 1990s, there was a need to use these APIs on computers that did not have hardware acceleration for 3D graphics.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] "Fallback" rendering implementations were provided that did not require special hardware, and these are sometimes called "software renderers" (today hardware acceleration is almost always available, and these CPU-only implementations are used primarily for testing).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] More recently, "software rendering" may also mean rendering that does not use graphics APIs such as OpenGL, Metal, Direct3D, or Vulkan.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Types of renderers that in the past might have been called "software renderers" (e.g. path tracing renderers used for offline rendering for movies) now commonly use GPU acceleration, often via APIs such as CUDA or OpenCL, which are not graphics-specific.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Since these latter APIs allow running C++ code on a GPU, it is now possible to run the same rendering code on either a CPU or GPU.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The following is a rough timeline of frequently mentioned rendering techniques, including areas of current research.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Note that even in cases where an idea was named in a specific paper, there were almost always multiple researchers or teams working in the same area (including earlier related work).
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When a method is first proposed it is often very inefficient, and it takes additional research and practical efforts to turn it into a useful technique.
[src:virtual-geometry-nanite/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The list focuses on academic research and does not include hardware.
